            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Mendoza Miller is a product of the San Francisco that existed long before the tech booms. Born in 1970, he was raised in the foggy, working-class avenues of the Excelsior District. His father, a white Navy veteran from Ohio, met his mother, a fiercely proud nurse from Cebu, Philippines, while stationed at Subic Bay. Their home was a blend of Midwestern pragmatism and Filipino warmth, filled with the smell of both pot roast and adobo.\n\nGrowing up, Kai was never an academic. He was the kid who took apart the family toaster to see how it worked. While his friends dreamed of college, Kai saw his future in schematics and wiring. The 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake was a defining moment; seeing the city's vital infrastructure crippled gave him a profound respect for the people who put it back together. He enrolled at City College of San Francisco, earning an Associate's degree in Electrical Technology. Soon after, he landed a coveted apprenticeship with the SFMTA.\n\nFor over three decades, Kai has been a Journey Line Worker, one of the unseen hands keeping the city's circulatory system\u2014the MUNI\u2014alive. He\u2019s spent countless nights under city streets, splicing high-voltage cables and maintaining the overhead lines that power the trolleys. His steady, union-backed career provided a stable anchor through the city's turbulent economic cycles. He watched the dot-com boom and bust with a wry amusement, his hands-on skills always in demand.\n\nHe met his wife, Elena, at a Mission High football game, and they\u2019ve been married for 28 years. They bought their modest Sunset District home in the late \u201890s, a move that now seems like winning the lottery. Their son, now 24, works in biotech, a world Kai finds both foreign and fascinating.\n\nKai\u2019s daily routine is a testament to his life\u2019s work. He leaves his home near Ocean Beach and catches the L Taraval, inspecting the overhead lines with a practiced eye as he rides towards the MUNI yard. He feels a quiet ownership of the system. His dream isn\u2019t to start a company or get rich; it\u2019s to retire in five years with a full pension, travel with Elena, and spend weekends working on his classic 1968 Ford Falcon. He is a living thread in San Francisco's fabric, a man who doesn\u2019t just live in the city, but actively powers its heart."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe must have been ten. It was a foggy Saturday in the Excelsior. His father, smelling of soap and Old Spice, was carving a pot roast at the head of the table. Then his mother came from the kitchen, her face beaming, carrying the big clay pot of chicken adobo, the vinegar and garlic scent filling the room. The two smells\u2014Ohio and Cebu\u2014mingled perfectly. It wasn't just dinner; it was the blueprint for his life. Two different worlds, working together in perfect, loving harmony.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the eerie silence after the shaking stopped in '89, the whole city holding its breath in the dust. The fear was real, but what stuck with him was the sight, days later, of a lone SFMTA crew working under floodlights to restore power to a darkened street. He watched them, a small team bringing a city back to life with their hands and their knowledge. In that moment, he didn't just see a job; he saw a purpose. His future wasn't in a book, it was in a schematic.\n\n3.\nHe wasn't even that interested in the Mission High football game. He was there with a buddy. Then he saw her, Elena, laughing with her friends under the cheap stadium lights. She wasn't wearing anything fancy, just a jean jacket, but her smile cut through the chilly night air. He felt a jolt\u2014not like the high-voltage lines he'd later master, but something just as powerful and infinitely warmer. He knew, with a certainty that surprised him, that he was looking at the rest of his life.\n\n4.\nA winter storm in the mid-2000s had snapped a major feeder cable near the Zoo, paralyzing the L and M lines. He remembers the rain stinging his face as he worked high in the bucket truck, the wind howling off the ocean. Down below, the city was dark and stalled. But up there, with his tools, there was only the delicate, high-stakes task of splicing the thick cable. When the lights of the MUNI Metro sign flickered back on, a deep, quiet pride settled in his chest. This was his city.\n\n5.\nHe remembers his son, home from his biotech job, trying to explain his work on \"crispr-based diagnostics.\" The words were alien, a language from the new San Francisco he saw but didn't belong to. Yet, as he watched his son\u2019s hands move with excitement, describing a world of invisible machinery, Kai felt a surge of pure pride. He keeps the city\u2019s heart beating; his son was learning to repair its very code. The work was different, but the builder's spirit, he realized, was exactly the same."
